    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the strength of concrete and steel rebar is a classic topic in civil engineering. Concrete is indeed strong in compression, but it's not as strong in tension. Steel rebar is introduced to provide tensile strength, as concrete can crack under tension forces. The compressive strength of concrete and the tensile strength of steel complement each other, creating a stronger and more durable foundation. Together, they can withstand various loads and forces acting on the structure. So, while concrete is strong in compression, steel rebar is what gives it the necessary tensile strength to handle tension forces. It's like having a strong, sturdy wall (concrete) and flexible, stretchy bands (steel rebar) working together to keep your house (foundation) standing strong.",
